[2
Date: Tue 30 Jan 2001 20:24:20 -0000
From: Pablo Nart <P.Nart@vet.gla.ac.uk>
Source: El Pais, ABC and Yahoo [edited

The Cantabria case [of suspected bovine spongiform encephalopathy (BSE)
that produced intense controversy, since the affected animal was only 30
months of age, has finally been declared inconclusive by the Laboratorio
Nacional de Referencia in Zaragoza.
So far 9 cases of BSE have been diagnosed in Spain. Dates and details taken
from the press are:
1- 23 Nov 2000, 5 years old, Rubia Gallega/Friesian breed. Galicia
2- 18 Dec 2000 a 5 years old, Heckviech breed. Galicia
3- 3 Jan 2001, 6 years old, Friesian breed. (Fed on concentrates and milk
substitutes until 4 months of age and after that age only on grain and
hay). Zamora
4- 3 Jan 2001, 5 years old, Friesian breed. Zamora
5- 6 Jan 2001, 5 years old, Friesian breed. Galicia
6- 15 Jan 2001, 5 years old, Friesian breed. Asturias
7- 16 Jan 2001, 5 years old, Mixed breed. Asturias
8- 17 Jan 2001, 4 years old, Friesian breed. Avila
9- 25 Jan 2001, 6 years old, Friesian breed. Zamora
In all cases the whole herd has been destroyed.
All cases but one have been detected in the northwest of Spain. Portugal is
tied with Ireland as the country in Europe with [the highest number of
positive cases (503), 80 per cent of them concentrated along the northwest
of the country. The Portuguese-Spanish border has traditionally been known
for its permeability. Animals graze both sides of the border along its 1250
km [length. Concentrates are 600 pesetas per bag (around US $3.50) cheaper
in Portugal, and since both countries are members of the EU there are no
controls in their borders.
So far only the Regional Basque Government has arranged the cremation of
the concentrates in the ovens of some cement plants. The medium term
implications are still unknown. The Ministry of Agriculture is dedicating
53 000 million pesetas (around US $300 million) this year to control the
disease.
The ban on feeding ruminants animal protein would impose some changes in
the beef sector. Veal, the most consumed meat in Spain, comes from animals
younger than 24 months, and will be difficult to produce in the future as
the growth of animals fed on vegetarian proteins will be slower.
The implications for the bullfighting sector are still being analyzed. To
preserve the breed there is discussion of avoiding the destruction of the
whole herd in case a positive animal is found. As most of the wounds in
bullfighting are made along the bull's spinal region, there is also
discussion about safety issues concerning the bullfighter and other
personnel involved in the spectacle.
No cases of [Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, the human variant of BSE have been
reported in Spain.
--
Pablo Nart
Clinical Scholar
Pathology Department
Faculty of Veterinary Medicine
University of Glasgow
<P.Nart@vet.gla.ac.uk>
