[3
Date: Wed 31 Jan 2001 10:53:59 -0500
From: Patricia Doyle, PhD <dr_p_doyle@hotmail.com>
Source: AP - Wed 31 Jan 2001 5:36 AM ET [edited
<http://dailynews.yahoo.com/h/ap/20010131/wl/mad_cow_1.html>

Germany to Slaughter Cattle
-----------------------------------
BERLIN: The German government announced [on Wednesday [31 Jan 2001 [that
it would slaughter an estimated 400 000 cattle in an attempt to curb mad
cow disease, a spokesman said. Agriculture minister Renate Kuenast had
estimated it would cost the country about $166 million to buy the cattle
from farmers, properly slaughter them, and dispose of the corpses. After
the animals are killed, they are to be tested for BSE.
German ministers had claimed their country was free of the disease until
the first case was discovered in November [2000. Since then, several cases
have been discovered every week, bringing the overall number of infected
cattle to more than 20. BSE has been linked with new variant
Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, the human version of the fatal brain-wasting
ailment that has killed some 80 Europeans since the mid-1990s, mostly in
Britain. Cattle parts ground back into feed are suspected of spreading the
disease.
--
Patricia Doyle, PhD
<dr_p_doyle@hotmail.com>
